          .content
            h1  #HoleInTheWall 
            p
              span.textLeft
                | To celebrate the release of Krispy Kreme's new Nutty Chocolatta doughnut, they wanted to create a spectical and launch the product in an interactive window display at the Holborn Store in London.
              span.textRight
                | Replacing the old shop front with a bespokely designed display, customers were able to use a contactless bank card to pay for a product, to begin the experience and receive their doughnut at the end.
          .videoContainer
            .videoPlayer
              iframe#player2.yPlayer(src='https://www.youtube.com/embed/AlvdRkRewvA?enablejsapi=1&loop=1&modestbranding=1&playlist=AlvdRkRewvA&rel=0&showinfo=0', frameborder='0', allowfullscreen='', width='560', height='315')
        #portfolio3page.animatingPage
          .content
            .textContainer
              h1  The Epic Mind Drive 
              p
                span.textLeft
                  | Celebrating the release of telematics boxes for insurees car's, MoneySupermarket.com wanted to reward smarter drivers with more than just cheaper car insurance. The Epic Mind Drive was launched to allow users to drive a car using their minds!
                span.textRight
                  | To do this, we used an Emotiv EEG headset to measure a users brain activity and translate that into a signal, that could then control the cars steering wheel and acceleration pad.
          .videoContainer
            .videoPlayer
              iframe#player3.yPlayer(src='https://www.youtube.com/embed/K3N18cqnzHg?enablejsapi=1&loop=1&modestbranding=1&playlist=K3N18cqnzHg&rel=0&showinfo=0', frameborder='0', allowfullscreen='', width='560', height='315')
        #portfolio4page.animatingPage
          .content
            .textContainer
              h1 Hacky Xmas
              p
                span.textLeft
                  | Kerve wanted to wish their clients a happy christmas in a fun and unusual way. Using an Arduino, Hacky xmas was an electronics powered card that hacked a users computer (in a fun, not scary way)!
                span.textRight
                  | Once the card was plugged into a pc's usb, a xmas tune was sung from the speakers and a web browser window was opened, which contained an addictive html5 game and a leaderboard filled with prizes.
          .videoContainer
            .videoPlayer
              iframe#player4.yPlayer(src='https://www.youtube.com/embed/d_NQcNYMKG8?enablejsapi=1&loop=1&modestbranding=1&playlist=d_NQcNYMKG8&rel=0&showinfo=0', frameborder='0', allowfullscreen='', width='560', height='315')
        #portfolio5page.animatingPage
          .content
            .textContainer
              h1  Pay @ Pump 
              p
                span.textLeft
                  | Focussed on demonstrating the possibilities of their contactless card payment system, Barclaycard's prototype 'Pay @ Pump' beer pump was designed to reduce queues at bars on a night out.
                span.textRight
                  | Using Payworks, NodeJS, arduino and electronics - the beer pump was automated to accurately pour a pints worth of beer once a successful payment had been received.
          .videoContainer
            .videoPlayer
              iframe#player5.yPlayer(src='https://www.youtube.com/embed/8ycTf2TDH_I?enablejsapi=1&loop=1&modestbranding=1&playlist=8ycTf2TDH_I&rel=0&showinfo=0', frameborder='0', allowfullscreen='', width='560', height='315')
        #portfolio6page.animatingPage
          .content
            .textContainer
              h1  What If You Were In 
              p
                span.textLeft
                  | This brief was about turning the frustration of waiting at a rail way crossing, into a playful and positive experience. Working with Ferran Altarriba, we created an installation which came to life when the barriers came down.
                span.textRight
                  | Consisting of a screen, computer and a Kinect - users could email where else they would rather be. The screen would then replace the background of where the viewers currently are and put them in the location of their choice.
          .videoContainer
            .videoPlayer
              iframe#player6.yPlayer(src='https://www.youtube.com/embed/Swuka5XJRcw?enablejsapi=1&loop=1&modestbranding=1&playlist=Swuka5XJRcw&rel=0&showinfo=0', frameborder='0', allowfullscreen='', width='560', height='315')
        #portfolio7page.animatingPage
